36: We present a tightened integrated account of the A10 cosmology program, whose central aim is to realize a high-$H_0$ early-universe solution while avoiding the large acoustic-phase distortions that typically accompany simpler constant-$\Delta N_{\rm eff}$ extensions. The program begins from a localized early-time energy-transfer branch centered near $z \approx 5000$, first posed phenomenologically and later implemented as a conversion from a quasi-vacuum parent component $Y$ to a stiff daughter component $X$ in a full perturbative treatment based on \textsc{CLASS}. The main phenomenological claim is that a sufficiently early and localized transfer can reduce the sound horizon while leaving the observed CMB acoustic structure substantially more controlled than in simpler benchmark modifications. We then promote the localized transfer from an externally imposed redshift kernel to a dynamically organized trigger by introducing a spectral-Horndeski stability window near $\chi \approx 137$. In this interpretation, the transfer is activated only when the scalar field enters a stability-protected domain. A complementary root-geometric analysis is retained, not as a literal cosmological derivation, but as a conceptual model of selectivity: narrow visible structures become non-generic unless leakage into bulk degrees of freedom is strongly suppressed. Within the reported Markov Chain Monte Carlo analysis of the gated branch, the preferred region reaches $H_0 \approx 73\,\mathrm{km\,s^{-1}\,Mpc^{-1}}$ together with a self-adjusted dark matter density $\omega_{\rm cdm} \approx 0.1087$. As a separate and explicitly optional extension, we also summarize a late-time momentum-drag sector for dark matter that produces only modest $S_8$ suppression while introducing a clear trade-off with CMB lensing consistency. The resulting interpretation is deliberately narrow: the A10 program supports a viable layered model class in which early-time phenomenology, field-space stability, and