24: \title{From Localized Early-Time Energy Transfer to 137-Stability Gating:\\
25: A Refined Integrated A10 Cosmology for the Hubble Tension\\
26: with an Optional Late-Time Growth-Suppression Extension}
27: \author{Keiji Yoshimura\\Independent Researcher}
28: \date{April 2026\\[0.5em]

34: 
35: \begin{abstract}
36: We present a tightened integrated account of the A10 cosmology program, whose central aim is to realize a high-$H_0$ early-universe solution while avoiding the large acoustic-phase distortions that typically accompany simpler constant-$\Delta N_{\rm eff}$ extensions. The program begins from a localized early-time energy-transfer branch centered near $z \approx 5000$, first posed phenomenologically and later implemented as a conversion from a quasi-vacuum parent component $Y$ to a stiff daughter component $X$ in a full perturbative treatment based on \textsc{CLASS}. The main phenomenological claim is that a sufficiently early and localized transfer can reduce the sound horizon while leaving the observed CMB acoustic structure substantially more controlled than in simpler benchmark modifications. We then promote the localized transfer from an externally imposed redshift kernel to a dynamically organized trigger by introducing a spectral-Horndeski stability window near $\chi \approx 137$. In this interpretation, the transfer is activated only when the scalar field enters a stability-protected domain. A complementary root-geometric analysis is retained, not as a literal cosmological derivation, but as a conceptual model of selectivity: narrow visible structures become non-generic unless leakage into bulk degrees of freedom is strongly suppressed. Within the reported Markov Chain Monte Carlo analysis of the gated branch, the preferred region reaches $H_0 \approx 73\,\mathrm{km\,s^{-1}\,Mpc^{-1}}$ together with a self-adjusted dark matter density $\omega_{\rm cdm} \approx 0.1087$. As a separate and explicitly optional extension, we also summarize a late-time momentum-drag sector for dark matter that produces only modest $S_8$ suppression while introducing a clear trade-off with CMB lensing consistency. The resulting interpretation is deliberately narrow: the A10 program supports a viable layered model class in which early-time phenomenology, field-space stability, and selective activation are designed together, but it does not by itself constitute final model selection over all alternatives.
37: \end{abstract}
38:

35: 
36: \begin{abstract}
37: This manuscript provides a v0.2.1 theory-freedom / strict-audit clarification for the A10 Core Foundation. It treats A10 not as a universal physical law and not as a domain-validated theory, but as a structured-prior methodology for building, testing, and publishing claim-bounded diagnostic branches. The contribution has three linked layers. First, it states the methodological core: construct hypotheses boldly, translate them into reduced surrogates or domain-specific models, compare them against baselines, audit ablations and failure boundaries, freeze holdout or negative-control tests where possible, and publish only the bounded claim that the evidence actually supports. Second, it formalizes the v0.2.1 operational rule that A10 expands theory-construction freedom, not claim-making permission: speculative hypotheses may enter the protocol, but only evidence-bounded claims may exit it. Third, it preserves the dense v0.1.2 localized early-time A10 cosmology branch as the principal historical case study rather than demoting it to a thin appendix. That case study includes a localized energy-transfer episode near $z \approx 5000$, a quasi-vacuum-to-stiff-fluid implementation, CMB/BAO comparisons, a spectral-Horndeski stability window near $\chi \approx 137$, a reported high-$H_0$ candidate region, root-geometric selectivity diagnostics, and an optional late-time momentum-drag extension. The integrated conclusion is deliberately limited: A10 Core is a portfolio-governance and structured-prior framework, while the cosmology branch is a reduced-surrogate and diagnostic case study, not a final Hubble-tension solution, not a universal model-selection result, and not observational discovery.
38: \end{abstract}
